===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# A [[lime]] and [[water]] [[mixture]] for [[painting]] walls and [[fence]]s [[bright]] [[white]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1952|author=L. F. Salzman|title=Building in England|page=157|passage=For walls plaster gave a smooth white surface; or if it was not sufficiently white, or had become discoloured, it could be brightened up with a coat of whitewash or paint.}}
# {{lb|en|sports}} A complete [[victory]] or series of victories without suffering any [[loss]]es; a [[clean sweep]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|author=Andrew Miller|title=Cricinfo|passage=For the first time in a long time, Australia are being threatened with the prospect of a 5-0 '''whitewash'''}}
# {{lb|en|politics}} A campaign to [[paper over]] unfavorable elements.
#: {{ant|en|blackwash}}
#* {{quote-web
|en
|date=2018-01-24
|author=Hannah Beech
|author2=Rick Gladstone
|title=Citing ‘Whitewash,’ Bill Richardson Quits Rohingya Post
|work=New York Times
|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/24/world/asia/bill-richardson-myanmar-rohingya.html
|passage=“She has developed an arrogance of power,” Mr. Richardson said by telephone during a layover in Tokyo on his way back to New Mexico from Myanmar. “I’ve known her a long time and am fond of her, but she basically is unwilling to listen to bad news, and I don’t want to be part of a '''whitewash'''.”}}
#* {{quote-web
|en
|date=2019-06-13
|author=Kalyeena Makortoff
|title=FCA report into RBS called a 'complete whitewash' by critics
|work=The Guardian
|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/jun/13/fca-report-into-rbs-branded-complete-whitewash
|passage=A report by the City watchdog into the scandal at Royal Bank of Scotland’s turnaround unit has been described as a '''whitewash''' after the regulator confirmed it would not punish the bank for mistreating business customers following the financial crash.}}
# {{lb|en|cooking}} The most basic type of [[thickening agent]], [[flour]] blended with water to make a paste.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Any liquid composition for [[whiten]]ing something, such as a wash for making the skin fair.
#* '''1713''', {{w|Joseph Addison}}, ''The Guardian''
#*:{{quote|en|I have heard a whole Sermon against a '''White-wash'''.}}
# {{lb|en|UK|slang|obsolete}} A glass of [[sherry]] as a [[finale]], after drinking [[port]] and [[claret]].
#* '''1883''', ''Cassell's Dictionary of Cookery'' (page lxxxiii)
#*: The bottles, however, were port bottles, but contained mushroom ketchup; and we can only say with regard to the 15s. sherry, that it would have made an admirable "'''whitewash'''," as Sheridan's glass is still sometimes called, {{...}}
#* '''1950''', ''Wine & the Wine Trade'' (page 28)
#*: Sercial was also used as a sort of '''white-wash''' after the Port at dinner, those were the days when people had time to drink both Port and a '''White wash'''.

