===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# To paint over with a lime and water mixture so as to brighten up a wall or fence.
#: {{ux|en|The houses looked very bright when they '''whitewashed''' the whole neighborhood.}}
# {{lb|en|figurative}} To cover over errors or bad actions.
#: {{ant|en|blackwash}}
#: {{ux|en|In his sermon, the minister didn't try to '''whitewash''' over the sins of his church.}}
#* {{quote-web
|en
|date=2015-11-12
|author=Se-Woong Koo
|title=South Korea’s Textbook Whitewash
|work=New York Times
|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/13/opinion/south-koreas-textbook-whitewash.html
|passage=The books have yet to be written. But there is no question that Ms. Park and her Saenuri Party will '''whitewash''' the past to bolster the conservative cause at the expense of the education system and South Korea’s international reputation as a democracy, and harm Seoul’s attempt to hold Japan accountable for its wartime conduct.}}
# {{lb|en|dated|transitive}} To [[repay]] the [[financial]] [[debt]]s of (another person).
#* {{Q|en|Dickens|The Pickwick Papers|43|quote=Meanwhile, Sam, having been formally introduced to the '''whitewashed''' gentleman and his friends, as the offspring of Mr. Weller, of the Belle Savage, was treated with marked distinction, and invited to regale himself with them in honour of the occasion—an invitation which he was by no means backward in accepting.}}
# {{lb|en|baseball|slang|dated|late|19th century|archaic}} To prevent a team from scoring any runs.
# {{lb|en|US|UK|slang}} In various games, to defeat (an opponent) so that they fail to score, or to reach a certain point in the game; to [[skunk]].
# {{lb|en|pejorative}} To [[make over]] (a person or character, a group, an event, etc) so that it is or seems more [[white]], for example by applying makeup to a person, or by discounting the participation of [[people of color]] in an event and focusing on only [[white]] participation.
#* {{quote-web|en|author=Ernest Owens|date=2015-06-08|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/ernest-owens/hollywood-dont-you-dare-w_b_7946860.html|work=HuffPost|title=Hollywood, Don't You Dare Whitewash Stonewall|passage=If you appreciate historical accuracy and fair inclusion, don’t go see this film. If you don’t want to fuel the economy at another Hollywood attempt of '''whitewashing''' American history, don’t give any aspect of this film a single dime or promotion.}} <!--not durable and so doesn't count towards ATTEST, but is acceptable as a good illustration of use-->
#* {{quote-web|en|title=Ghost in the Shell’s whitewashing: does Hollywood have an Asian problem?|author=Steve Rose|date=2017-03-31|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/mar/31/ghost-in-the-shells-whitewashing-does-hollywood-have-an-asian-problem|passage=From Scarlett Johansson’s heroine in the remake of the anime classic to Tilda Swinton as a Himalayan high priest in Doctor Strange, the film industry stands accused of '''whitewashing''' Asian characters and culture. Does it have a defence?}}
#* {{quote-web|en|title=Naomi Osaka sponsor apologises for 'whitewashing' tennis star in ad|author=Justin McCurry|date=2019-01-23|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/jan/23/naomi-osaka-sponsor-apologises-for-whitewashing-tennis-star-in-ad|passage=The ad, which also features her compatriot Kei Nishikori, drew criticism on social media, with many users accusing Nissin of '''whitewashing''' Osaka, whose mother is Japanese.}}

